      <div class="msgContentFrame">I cant think of many lap tops that can be upgraded outside of the ram and HD. <br /> <br />Network cards and graphics cards are 99% of the time stuck.  You can add a pci network card, but thats about it. <br /> <br />If you insist on using a laptop do the following: <br />Make sure it has a dedicated g card and not an onboard one.  This may sound like a no-duh type statement but youd be suprised <br /> <br />Make sure the ram isn't already caped out, some come with 4~8gigs of ram and thats the most they can handle, find one that can handle up to 16~32.  You may never need it but you never know. <br /> <br />Gonna venture a wild guess, but buy a hard surface to place the laptop on, something flat.  A laptop straight on your lap or set on a bed can over heat and ruin the gcard/over heat the cpu fast.   If your laptops arent lasting more then 2-3 years over heatting is the most likely culprit.  I use a cheapo targu laptop fan. its 12 x 13in and has 2 fans on it.  My laptop never is set on anything other then a hard flat surface either.  No carpet, and not my lap. <br /> <br /> <br />All in all, dont go mac if you want games, they aren't more durable, they just use all first party components so there is less compatability issues and it makes them slight more crash resistant.  If a mac breaks your more sol then a regular laptop because theres less you can change out / repair on a mac.  </div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
        <div class="msgFtFrameFix"></div>
