      <div class="msgContentFrame">Hi.  I've been running FFXI on my MacBook Pro (early 2008 model) without difficulty for a while.  The main issue with it is that the virtual machines (Parallels, VMWare, etc.) don't really do well with FFXI.  Go search the Internet with keywords like FFXI, Mac, and virtual, and you'll find plenty of conversations about how difficult it is to make that work out.  Even the threads saying &quot;I made it work&quot; usually describe degraded performance, and having to figure out other possibilities like Ubuntu installations is really a pain in the posterior. <br /> <br />So, to run FFXI on a Mac, you'll be installing Windows via Boot Camp.  My Boot Camp Windows XP Pro SP3 installation is the most stable Windows install I've ever had; my PC-based installs, frankly, all sucked a lot.  I'm sure there are ways to tweak those installs to work better, but I am not the one to ask about that.  The Apple-haters on this thread probably have good advice along those lines.  Anyway, Boot Camp is pretty easy to set up, as long as you have a Windows install disc that has Win XP SP2 or later, all on one disc.  You can't change discs mid-stream.  It's almost trivial to slipstream in SP2 or SP3 though, and any Mac you'd be buying now should be able to handle Windows 7 as well.  The major complaint I have with Boot Camp is that if I'm on my Mac partition and see something pop up on the auction house, or get an IM asking for help with something, I have to restart into my Windows partition, wait for that to finish starting up, and go log in.  It's really only a minute or two, but when you're anxious to get into the game, that's an annoying wait. <br /> <br />The thing does seem to get warm sometimes when I'm playing FFXI or Civ 5, but the temps I've read have been well within the specified tolerances. <br /> <br />tl;dr: Yes, you can run FFXI on a Mac.</div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
        <div class="msgFtFrameFix"></div>
