      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">Laptops can't be easily upgraded. Macs are notorious for being impossible to upgrade outside of swapping the RAM. Combine the 2, and you're SOL.</div></div> <br /> <br />Macs are no more or less upgradeable than anything else with the same form factor. There have been some models of Macs where getting to much besides the RAM is a bitch and a half...but their current lineup isn't really like that. There are quite a number of PC laptops that are significantly harder to take apart. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">If a mac breaks your more sol then a regular laptop because theres less you can change out / repair on a mac.</div></div> <br /> <br />Not really true. Apple's long product cycles are hell on their performance for the dollar, and their relatively slim selection is annoying at times too...but it does mean that you can pretty readily find parts for them compared to the 30-40 model variants HP might have for the US market alone at any given time. Cost, however, is another matter. <br /> <br />Anyway... <br /> <br />Macs use nearly the same hardware that PCs do - the only real exception is that they don't have a BIOS, and instead use EFI...which generic PCs were supposed to swap over to 5 years ago or so, but never did (rumor has it that UEFI will be more common for the upcoming Sandy Bridge machines). They're nicely designed and constructed, but not necessarily more durable. <br /> <br />Purely from a hardware standpoint, you can run anything on a Mac that you could on a PC with the same hardware specs. For games, you'd most likely wind up dual-booting Windows and playing games on the Windows side - though some things may run acceptably via virtual machines or WINE. <br /> <br />One key point comes in with software. If you're self-employed, in design, you probably have a fair bit invested in software, assuming you do things legally. Swapping platforms would mean repurchasing a lot of that software, adding even more to the cost. You also would want to look at whether or not everything you use is even on the platform. <br />Buying a Mac just to boot Windows on it 90% of the time doesn't make a lot of sense.  <br /> <br />If you're hard on machines, also be aware that their comprehensive warranty coverage options are somewhat lacking compared to other companies. Apple doesn't offer accidental damage coverage. Third parties might offer it for their hardware, but Apple doesn't. Part of my job involves supporting laptops given to scholarship athletes and the like, so believe me, I've seen a lot of busted laptops.  <br /> <br />I'd echo the sentiment that you really want to go with a desktop as a primary gaming machine, if possible. A half-decent discrete GPU will let you play some games on the road, but if you focus too much on the gaming angle, you're going to wind up with a machine that sucks as an actual portable...and will be behind the curve in a year or two anyway. <br /> <br />Of the companies I've dealt with, I'd vouch for Dell when it coms to easily getting service. HP isn't great. Sony is absolute, unmitigated crap. Dell actually tends to have a tech out next day. They've made some mistakes, but not as many as others. If you want a gaming portable from them, they tend to point you at their Alienware machines now, though they did just refresh their XPS line. I've only used the M11x, but if that's any indication, the M15x should be fairly good too. <br /> <br />Again though, buy the good warranty. That'll do a LOT more for the computer woes you've described than buying a machine with better industrial design and coffee-house cred.  <br /> <br />Not trying to be a hater or whatever. Personally, I've owned at least one Mac of some kind for about 15 years now, along with other platforms of course. I've supported them at work for about 10 years. I'm typing this on a Mac Pro. There are reasons to buy one, and if you simply want a Mac, then fine too. Just saying, the reasons you stated for looking at them...don't make sense based on my experience.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><span class="sm"><span style="color:Orange"></span> <b><a href="HTTP://www.ffxiah.com/player.php?id=298541" rel="external nofollow" title="www.ffxiah.com/player.php?id=298541"><span style="color:Orange">Isiolia</span></a></b> - Mithra - <i>Pandemo...</i> <i>Asura</i> FU SE <span style="color:Orange"></span> <br /><span style="color:silver">RDM BLM BST BRD NIN WAR PLD DNC BLU</span></span></div></div>
