      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Isiolia wrote:</div><div class="orig"> <br /> <br />Purely from a hardware standpoint, you can run anything on a Mac that you could on a PC with the same hardware specs. For games, you'd most likely wind up dual-booting Windows and playing games on the Windows side - though some things may run acceptably via virtual machines or WINE. <br /> <br />One key point comes in with software. If you're self-employed, in design, you probably have a fair bit invested in software, assuming you do things legally. Swapping platforms would mean repurchasing a lot of that software, adding even more to the cost. You also would want to look at whether or not everything you use is even on the platform. <br />Buying a Mac just to boot Windows on it 90% of the time doesn't make a lot of sense.</div></div> <br /> <br />Isiolia brings up a great point.  Repurchasing software is truly annoying, and a lot of design software (as you know) is expensive.  One other minor issue I forgot to mention is that Microsoft stopped supporting Internet Explorer on Mac a while ago (version 5, maybe?).  The only problem with that is some sites don't believe in using code which is platform-independent - especially some corporate sites, although that's probably not a big issue for a self-employed person - and that can make it harder to get stuff done on a Mac if you rely on those sites. <br /> <br />I'm not saying that all PC machines suck, and only Macs are awesome.  There are good reasons to buy both.  Hopefully you at least got your original question answered, though.</div>
